<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-03-16T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-03-16T12:00:00-05:00" n="481" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d481">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">251.11 Insull, Samuel/371:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-03-16T19:00:00+02:00">March 16, 1934—7
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 16—3:36 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>34. The Minister now informs me that the <hi rend="italic">Maiotis</hi> has been ordered by wireless to return at once to
                                Piraeus. He explained that as the fugitive has no papers to enter
                                Egypt he must have arranged some further stratagem which this action
                                may forestall.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>